    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1966-10-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1966-10-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="400"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d400">
                <head>400. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d400fn1"
                        >Source: National Archives and Records Administration, RG 59, Central Files
                        1964–66, <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> 6. Confidential; <gloss
                            target="#t_Exdis1">Exdis</gloss>. Drafted by Toon on October 18 and
                        cleared in <gloss target="#t_S1">S</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_SS1"
                            >S/S</gloss> on October 19.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1966-10-10">October 10,
                            1966</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>United Nations Problems</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="italic">U.S.</hi>
                        <list>
                            <item>The Secretary</item>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_FWC2">William C. Foster</persName>—<gloss
                                    target="#t_ACDA1">ACDA</gloss>
                            </item>
                            <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_TLET1">Llewellyn
                                    Thompson</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Governor <persName corresp="#p_HWA2">Harriman</persName>
                            </item>
                            <pb facs="0906" n="872" xml:id="pg_872"/>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_LJM2">John M. Leddy</persName>-<gloss
                                    target="#t_EUR1">EUR</gloss>
                            </item>
                            <item>Malcolm Tonn—<gloss target="#t_SOV1">SOV</gloss>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_USSR1">
                            <hi rend="italic">U.S.S.R.</hi>
                        </gloss>
                        <list>
                            <item>Foreign Minister <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Soviet Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_DAF1">Antoliy
                                    Dobrynin</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Alexander I. Zinchunk, Minister-Counselor, Soviet Embassy</item>
                            <item>Counselor of Embassy Vorontosov</item>
                            <item>Ivan I. Ippolitov, Aide to <persName corresp="#p_GAA1"
                                    >Gromyko</persName>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>The Secretary asked Mr. <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName> if he had
                    given any thought to the problems we faced in the United Nations in view of the
                    expansion of membership far beyond our original expectations when we worked out
                    the Charter. Clearly, some way has to be found to prevent the small nations,
                    whose financial participation in United Nations operations was minimal, from
                    assuming a dominating role. One possible solution might be a weighted vote
                    scheme. Another which particularly intrigued the Secretary was to make the
                        <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> budget subject to Security Council
                    recommendation but without a veto. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_GAA1"
                        >Gromyko</persName> said that the Soviet Union would readily support the
                    Security Council idea but did not comment on the veto point.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d400fn2">In an October 17 memorandum to <persName corresp="#p_GAJ1"
                            >Goldberg</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_SJJ1">Sisco</persName>
                        reported that <persName corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName> had told him that
                        during a private discussion following this talk <persName corresp="#p_GAA1"
                            >Gromyko</persName> had indicated “the likelihood of a Soviet voluntary
                        contribution.” (Ibid., <gloss target="#t_SS1">S/S</gloss> Files: Lot 76 D
                        435)</note>
                </p>
            </div>
